num.of.estimate <- 1000000 
sample.medians <- numeric(num.of.estimate) 
 
for (i in seq_len(num.of.estimate)) { 
  n <- 10 
  x <- rnorm(n, mean = 7, sd = 2) 
  # Compute median
  sample.medians[i] <- median(x)
}

mean(sample.medians) # Based on definition of Biasedness
## [1] 7.001394

Question 3

set.seed(1)

num.of.estimate <- 1000000 
sample.midranges <- numeric(num.of.estimate) 
 
for (i in seq_len(num.of.estimate)) { 
  n <- 10 
  x <- rnorm(n, mean = 7, sd = 2) 
  # Compute mid-range
  sample.midranges[i] <- (min(x)+max(x))/2
}

mean(sample.midranges) # Based on definition of Biasedness
## [1] 7.000625
cat("Because mean of the sample mid-range equals mean = 7, sample mid-range is an unbiased estimator for  under normal distribution." , "\n")
## Because mean of the sample mid-range equals mean = 7, sample mid-range is an unbiased estimator for  under normal distribution.

Question 8

What is the MoM estimator for b using the 1st moment ()?

Since () = (0+b)/2 for uniform distribution, b = 2*()

What is undesirable about this estimator?

For Unif[0, 100], if I take 0, 2, 10 from it, the () = 4, 2*() = 8 but actual b = 100.

Another example, the list {10,0,0,0,0} has a mean = 2. It results in estimating b = 4. But the actual max element is 10.

The MoM estimator for the parameters of a uniform distribution can be biased, particularly when the sample size is small. This means that, on average, the estimator may not provide an accurate estimate of the true parameter values.

From https://stats.stackexchange.com/questions/52688/method-of-moments-for-t-distribution the ML estimate is some sort of robust mean, with tails downweighted, as opposed to MM-based brute force arithmetic mean.
